This sigma value is different than our expected sigma value of (expected signal yield)/((expected background yield)^(1/2)). In order to get our sigma to match our expected value we'll need to make some mass cuts. We'll start by calculating our 2sigma significance, and then getting rid of all mass above and below the value corresponding to our 2 sigma significance.

Cutting off above and below two sigma leaves 25.852% of our original 100000 data points, meaning we are left with 25.852% of our distribution. This corresponds to an Nqcd of 517.04. In our signal distribution we are left with 33.051% of our original 100000 data points, corresponding to Nsignal of 16.5255. This returns a significance of 0.727sigma. We can see that using this mass cut we did not retain the majority of our signal data points. However, the majority of our signal data points were lost when we cut above the 2sigma threshold. Raising our upper and lower threshold cuts should return better results. We can see much of our signal mass is below 130, so we'll use that as our upper threshold, and calculate 1 sigma to use as our lower threshold.
